WEBVTT

00:00.194 --> 00:00.795
Good morning, everyone.

00:00.815 --> 00:04.659
My name is Luke, and I get to serve as the campus pastor at Canexus Aurelia.

00:05.039 --> 00:08.122
Shout out to those of you joining us from Aurelia and joining us online.

00:08.503 --> 00:17.632
And I'd love to lead off this morning by asking you, if you could describe Christmas in one word, what would that word be?

00:19.114 --> 00:26.642
Like when you think of the traditions or the experiences or those things that you're most looking forward to, what would that one word be?

00:28.258 --> 00:32.605
My guess is for some of you here, you'd think of a word like gifts or shopping.

00:33.145 --> 00:34.508
Maybe expensive.

00:36.350 --> 00:38.233
Maybe a word like Turkey comes to mind.

00:38.253 --> 00:43.181
Maybe a name like Santa or Rudolph.

00:43.201 --> 00:45.424
But what would that one word be for you?

00:46.966 --> 00:52.655
My guess is that for many of you in the room, it would kind of lean towards the positive, the happy, the joyful.

00:54.358 --> 00:57.202
But what happens if something

00:57.442 --> 01:01.127
goes really sideways in your Christmas.

01:01.988 --> 01:07.596
What happens if you're reflecting on Christmases that have gone way off the rails?

01:09.118 --> 01:10.560
A bit of a personal confession.

01:10.760 --> 01:14.085
I was a hyper kid, and I can sometimes still be a hyper adult.

01:14.105 --> 01:15.567
I know it doesn't show that much, but it's true.

01:16.588 --> 01:23.538
And what that means is that when you're a hyper person, sometimes unintentionally, you break things.

01:24.194 --> 01:27.459
Not intentionally, but it kind of shatters other people's peace and calm.

01:27.519 --> 01:30.203
And Christmas is a time where people really value that.

01:31.305 --> 01:38.496
Well, when I was about 14 years old, my family got together with some really good family friends for a Christmas dinner.

01:38.616 --> 01:40.159
And it was amazing.

01:40.199 --> 01:49.012
Like you can imagine, you know, the mashed potatoes with the melted butter, just like drizzling all over it, the turkey, the stuffing, just all the best things.

01:49.032 --> 01:52.818
And we'd had this wonderful meal, this really positive time together.

01:53.218 --> 02:08.160
And the table had been cleared and the parents were kind of relaxing sitting in their comfy sweaters and their cozy socks and sipping their hot beverages and just exhaling as you do at the end of a big Christmas event.

02:09.482 --> 02:12.727
And I was upstairs with the boys preparing to play contact football.

02:14.069 --> 02:15.211
What you do after Christmas dinner?

02:15.271 --> 02:17.234
You see, one of my friends had gotten

02:17.410 --> 02:19.073
a football for Christmas.

02:19.193 --> 02:22.678
So obviously, logically, the next thing you do is play contact football inside.

02:22.898 --> 02:23.419
You understand?

02:23.459 --> 02:30.130
So the game starts, he's at quarterback, he drops back, I'm running around, and he fires this pass through the air for me.

02:30.671 --> 02:33.014
It's a great pass, but it's just out of reach.

02:34.937 --> 02:36.339
So I had a decision to make.

02:37.521 --> 02:45.874
There's the responsible option, slow down, miss the pass, don't damage anything or anyone, or

02:47.074 --> 02:48.959
accelerate and dive.

02:49.941 --> 02:55.957
Now, being a self-respecting teenage boy who's competitive, I did the opposite, the obvious thing, I accelerated.

02:56.418 --> 02:58.002
But I didn't accelerate without

02:58.082 --> 03:07.033
Totally thinking about this because see my friend's bed was against the far wall of the room and I was like, I can dive, catch this football, land on the bed, best athletic play of the year.

03:07.414 --> 03:17.507
That's what I do, I accelerate, I dive, I pull in the football, I grab it and I land with a crash with all my weight on my friend's bed and I'm like, man, I wish that was on video, that was stellar.

03:19.529 --> 03:23.154
Except, have you ever tried?

03:23.362 --> 03:30.876
running as fast as you can, jumping as high as you can and landing with all your weight on just kind of like an average, maybe Ikea, double bed.

03:33.401 --> 03:39.832
That thing snapped into that football game one sideways real quick.

03:39.893 --> 03:47.186
In fact, that Christmas gathering, my parents wrapped that up real quick and it was a very quiet car ride home.

03:47.778 --> 03:57.748
And I think if you had pulled the parents aside on that particular day and said, hey, if you could describe this Christmas in one word, what would it be?

03:59.710 --> 04:02.493
Chaotic, unfortunate, expensive?

04:02.953 --> 04:03.874
Like do we get a phrase?

04:03.914 --> 04:05.256
We're putting our son up for adoption.

04:05.336 --> 04:06.137
That's what it's gonna be.

04:08.479 --> 04:15.346
You see, sometimes it just takes one messy, crazy, unscripted event to make a lot of things go sideways.

04:17.314 --> 04:24.961
And for many of you in this room, it's not just Christmas or the Christmas season, but there's been a lot that's gone sideways.

04:26.643 --> 04:31.147
And if I were to say to you, how would you describe Christmas in one word?

04:31.187 --> 04:44.580
You've been so under the gun in work or family responsibilities or circumstances that are just taking it out of you that you just say exhausted.

04:45.881 --> 04:46.802
I'm just

04:46.978 --> 04:50.162
exhausted and this is just one more thing to get through.

04:52.605 --> 05:10.226
Some of you are in a place where last Christmas you had a significant other and things were looking good and you're excited that this relationship might go the distance and then it didn't and something changed and you're dreading Christmas because it's going to be a lonely Christmas and that's your word lonely.

05:12.002 --> 05:17.568
You're going to have to show up at another family function without someone on your arm and deal with great Aunt Gertrude's questions.

05:18.750 --> 05:29.162
But when you're going to get married or something like that, for some of you, between last Christmas and this Christmas, someone you love passed away.

05:30.604 --> 05:33.327
And there's going to be an empty seat at the table for Christmas dinner.

05:34.949 --> 05:37.031
And that is incredibly painful.

05:37.251 --> 05:39.474
And in your word is that it's pain.

05:42.690 --> 05:48.197
I wonder if we could have a real honest conversation what your word would be.

05:49.979 --> 06:09.522
And what's hard is that whether it's somebody being hyperactive and snapping a bed in half like me, or whether it's something you've been living with and caring for a long time, it can take one really hard thing to hijack the whole Christmas season for you, unless God offers you a joy.

06:10.402 --> 06:17.110
that can transform your life and circumstances and sustain you, not just in the Christmas season, but throughout the year.

06:19.413 --> 06:37.554
But if you are going to really understand what that joy is, you need to understand to start the incredible reality of God's good plans for humanity, the good things that He has done for you.

06:39.202 --> 06:43.831
You see, every world religion says, all right, you want to do this?

06:44.632 --> 06:45.955
Here's a list of rules.

06:46.095 --> 06:47.197
Here's what you've got to do.

06:47.217 --> 06:50.323
Here's the things you have to do for God.

06:53.229 --> 07:02.386
But Christmas sets Christianity apart by totally changing that because Christmas starts out by saying, this is what God has done for you.

07:04.866 --> 07:10.211
There's a scholar a guy named Tim Keller, and he's got a great quote on this, what God is doing for us.

07:10.271 --> 07:19.460
He says, Christianity is about God through the form of his son, Jesus, arriving in our world in the form of a fragile human baby.

07:20.281 --> 07:22.263
It's about God ministering to our needs.

07:22.303 --> 07:28.169
It's about God dying for our sins, being buried in a tomb and being raised to life before eyewitnesses.

07:28.269 --> 07:33.554
Christmas is all about starting with what God has done for.

07:36.482 --> 07:45.216
And so in the verses we're looking at today, Mary actually helps us to orient our hearts to this incredible reality what God is doing for humanity.

07:45.997 --> 07:53.209
That he is the wonderful counselor whose plans and purposes are so incredible and so much greater than our own.

07:53.269 --> 08:01.522
That we have so much to gain by opening our lives to him and exactly wants that he wants to do in us and through us.

08:02.722 --> 08:06.866
So Mary's gonna show us what it looks like to be dialed into what God is doing for us.

08:08.207 --> 08:10.650
And also how you can respond to what God has done for you.

08:11.951 --> 08:14.714
A quick recap, remember Mary is a young woman.

08:15.194 --> 08:17.536
She's engaged to be married.

08:17.556 --> 08:30.469
And as Denil spoke about last week, she has an encounter with the angel Gabriel and discovers that not only is there a need for God to send someone to bring hope and rescue into the world, but that God wants to do that through Mary.

08:30.629 --> 08:31.730
And her response is,

08:31.842 --> 08:32.963
What the heck?

08:34.525 --> 08:40.891
She has very real doubts and uncertainties as to what God's plan means for her and for the world.

08:42.212 --> 08:45.275
But she chooses humble surrender and she chooses to serve.

08:45.355 --> 09:01.010
And so today in the verses that we're going to dive into together, we see Mary adopting this posture of joyfully celebrating the wonder of God's counsel, of God's good designs and embracing the joy of his purposes.

09:02.018 --> 09:07.083
So let's dive in looking at verses 46 to 49 of Luke chapter one.

09:07.484 --> 09:08.825
Mary says this.

09:09.686 --> 09:31.730
Have you ever noticed what happens when a woman gets engaged?

09:32.194 --> 09:35.599
Maybe you're that person and you know what it's like to get engaged.

09:35.619 --> 09:42.409
There's a picture they're gonna pop up in a second and it's from my engagement photo shoot with my wife, Emily, and yes, I know what you're thinking.

09:43.150 --> 09:44.572
You're thinking, that guy married up.

09:45.814 --> 09:46.835
And you're right, you're right.

09:46.956 --> 09:49.479
Some people wonder if she's being paid under the table to hang out with me.

09:49.660 --> 09:51.783
I don't know, but it's a win for me, 100%.

09:52.704 --> 09:59.474
But if you ever notice what happens when a woman gets engaged, like her whole life just shifts into high gear.

09:59.554 --> 10:01.777
All right, there's like, who are my bridesmaids gonna be?

10:02.017 --> 10:03.118
Oh, I gotta go dress shopping.

10:03.138 --> 10:05.061
And dress shopping is, man, that's an ordeal.

10:05.081 --> 10:06.703
There's a lot going on, a lot of things to try on.

10:06.983 --> 10:10.527
Dress shopping, centerpieces, invites, wedding colors.

10:10.767 --> 10:11.689
Who's gonna sit with who?

10:11.749 --> 10:12.730
Who can't sit with who?

10:12.970 --> 10:13.931
Who makes the guest list?

10:14.112 --> 10:15.393
Who doesn't make the guest list?

10:15.413 --> 10:18.016
Who has to make the guest list that I wish wouldn't make the guest list?

10:18.617 --> 10:19.378
You get the picture.

10:20.399 --> 10:26.827
Because it's an event that is marked by incredible anticipation and preparation.

10:28.749 --> 10:29.490
Mary,

10:29.570 --> 10:30.431
is no exception.

10:30.712 --> 10:31.933
She's an engaged woman.

10:32.554 --> 10:35.879
She's anticipating and preparing for her wedding day.

10:35.919 --> 10:37.461
She's dreaming of this day.

10:37.741 --> 10:43.209
She's looking forward to marriage to Joseph and building a life with him and having a family with him.

10:44.951 --> 10:48.276
And her life has just been turned upside down.

10:48.716 --> 10:51.540
And this is supposed to be one of the biggest days of her life.

10:53.022 --> 10:55.826
And I can't speak for you, but my guess is,

10:56.130 --> 11:04.999
When you are anticipating and preparing for a big event and something happens that totally compromises that or cancels that, you're not a happy camper.

11:06.080 --> 11:09.923
In fact, maybe that unwanted change of plans brings out the control freakin' you.

11:09.943 --> 11:12.526
It definitely does in me.

11:14.327 --> 11:22.796
And what's crazy about Christmas is that it tends to bring out the control freak in all of us.

11:24.477 --> 11:25.298
Consider for a second,

11:25.666 --> 11:27.569
You're decorating your Christmas tree.

11:28.310 --> 11:35.780
And suddenly you realize that you're that person that has to just have all the ornaments just so or else.

11:38.523 --> 11:41.527
Or it's time to put on Christmas music.

11:42.068 --> 11:44.051
And somebody fires something up and you're like, what is this?

11:44.211 --> 11:47.215
We start with Mariah Carey, baby, all I want for Christmas is you.

11:47.235 --> 11:48.437
We do not deviate from that.

11:48.777 --> 11:51.801
Bing Crosby is next, followed by Carey Underwood.

11:52.142 --> 11:53.584
Then Glee, like you've got it.

11:53.624 --> 11:55.346
Matt felt like, this is how we do this.

11:55.810 --> 12:08.705
Maybe you're a man in the room and you know what it's like to hit December 24th, wake up and say, oh my goodness, not only has my wife got all the gifts for all the people, including all the children and me, I don't have a gift for her.

12:08.845 --> 12:21.159
And suddenly you find yourself in a packed mall with angry, crazy people thinking very un-Christmas thoughts and driving out of a parking lot where you're shouting very un-Christmas things at the other people around you in their vehicles.

12:21.559 --> 12:24.242
You see Christmas brings out the control freak

12:24.514 --> 12:25.075
and all of us.

12:25.155 --> 12:28.298
And maybe if you're honest with yourselves, like, are there any control freaks in the room?

12:28.578 --> 12:29.279
No, don't raise your hands.

12:29.319 --> 12:29.939
Don't raise your hands.

12:30.320 --> 12:32.021
Your family and close friends already know who you are.

12:35.324 --> 12:39.448
And Mary shows us a better way.

12:40.189 --> 12:53.682
You see, control breeds entitlement and our false narratives that we can control the people around us can make it easy to think that you're entitled to certain things.

12:54.946 --> 13:09.250
But Mary lays down control and chooses to open her heart to wonder because entitlement actually kills wonder, but wonder builds and nurtures and fosters joy.

13:10.973 --> 13:17.263
And Mary chooses to say, I am confident that you are doing something good and glorious.

13:17.724 --> 13:21.490
And so I'm opening my life and surrendering

13:21.602 --> 13:28.409
to your plans, they don't all make perfect sense, but you're the wonderful counselor and I can trust your ways.

13:29.470 --> 13:35.075
That opens Mary's life to the joy of what God wants to do in her, for her, and through her.

13:36.196 --> 13:43.864
And when you follow Mary's example and open your life in the same way, you're opening up your life to what God wants to do in you and for you and through you.

13:44.965 --> 13:50.290
And that's why Mary uses language like saying, this is what God has done for me.

13:51.202 --> 13:53.265
She's got zero social standing.

13:53.285 --> 13:54.868
She's from a backwater town.

13:56.270 --> 14:01.339
She's very unknown, and yet God is acting decisively for her.

14:03.021 --> 14:09.953
Now, keep in mind, keep in mind that Mary is not saying perfect exactly what I wanted, unplanned pregnancy.

14:10.313 --> 14:12.397
This is going to boost my social standing.

14:12.417 --> 14:13.138
This is great.

14:13.506 --> 14:15.990
You know, this is going to make my life so much more simple and straightforward.

14:16.010 --> 14:20.116
This is going to be a really straightforward conversation to have with my family or with my fiance.

14:20.156 --> 14:21.478
It's going to be great.

14:23.080 --> 14:35.378
No, she's captivated in her heart and mind with the reality that God is doing something on a cosmic level and she has the joy of playing a central part in that.

14:36.994 --> 14:49.589
When Pastor writes about this and about Mary's response in this moment saying she's been caught up holy and her thinking is convinced her feelings are captivated and her will is gladly surrendered.

14:51.111 --> 14:57.719
Mary marvels that God chooses to use her in part because she has such an awesome view of God.

14:57.740 --> 14:59.982
She says, for the mighty one is holy.

15:00.022 --> 15:01.504
That means he's set apart.

15:01.584 --> 15:03.026
He is supreme.

15:03.746 --> 15:12.479
And one of the challenges for you and I is that sometimes we can think about Jesus as like a homeless puppy kind of on the doorstep of our hearts kind of like scratching at the door wanting to be let in.

15:13.401 --> 15:24.658
And Jesus does become vulnerable and weak and dependent entering this world as a baby to relate to you and your vulnerability and dependence and weakness.

15:25.538 --> 15:39.275
But he is also the creator and king who can inject himself into creation to do exactly what he wants, like a master architect can introduce something new in the design of something they're creating because he's God.

15:40.997 --> 15:51.630
And Mary is rightfully orienting herself and saying, you're God and I'm your servant and you're doing amazing things and you've invited me to be a part of what you're doing.

15:52.451 --> 15:53.032
Thank you.

15:53.753 --> 15:54.514
Thank you, God.

15:55.938 --> 16:15.824
And I wonder in this season, especially looking back on the reality of what has taken place in your life this year, especially with regards to your proximity and involvement here at Kinexis, if somewhere to say, what has God done for you this year?

16:16.685 --> 16:17.947
What comes to mind?

16:20.109 --> 16:23.634
What comes from mind to me is things like 50 people

16:23.714 --> 16:31.684
baptized in the spring saying, I want to live for Jesus and telling stories about healing and heart transformation and overcoming addiction.

16:31.824 --> 16:32.525
It's incredible.

16:34.127 --> 16:39.614
I think of sacred homecoming just a couple months ago, and the life changed so many people experience.

16:39.634 --> 16:42.137
I think, man, what has God done for you?

16:43.538 --> 16:46.702
Because I can see so many ways God has done so much for me.

16:48.585 --> 16:53.010
Mary opens her life to God to receive exactly what

16:53.186 --> 16:56.634
He intends to do for her and through her.

16:58.057 --> 17:07.337
But she continues by having some really compelling insights with regard to what it looks like to respond to and receive what God is doing.

17:07.377 --> 17:09.582
Let me read verses 50 to 53 for you.

17:10.524 --> 17:11.346
Mary says,

17:11.554 --> 17:14.859
He shows mercy from generation to generation to all who fear him.

17:15.220 --> 17:17.663
His mighty arm has done tremendous things.

17:18.144 --> 17:19.927
He has scattered the proud and haughty ones.

17:20.187 --> 17:23.913
He has brought down princes from their thrones and exalted the humble.

17:24.173 --> 17:28.480
He has filled the hungry with good things and sent the rich away with empty hands.

17:29.762 --> 17:37.473
You know, if you think across the board, what was it like to be a Canadian this past year, especially living in Simcoe County?

17:38.455 --> 17:40.658
Would you say it was magnificent

17:41.442 --> 17:45.608
Or did you say it was a bit messy or is even a marathon at times?

17:47.290 --> 17:47.911
Recap the year.

17:48.652 --> 17:50.395
Prime Minister resigns to start.

17:50.415 --> 17:50.955
Strong start.

17:51.396 --> 17:51.616
Wow.

17:52.838 --> 17:54.601
Kind of a polarizing election.

17:56.784 --> 17:59.207
Cost of living, going way up.

17:59.928 --> 18:02.211
Like I never knew Q-tips cost this much.

18:03.914 --> 18:05.917
Rising homelessness and poverty.

18:07.399 --> 18:09.682
AI, threatening job security.

18:10.434 --> 18:15.962
And oh, hey, let's throw in an ice storm just for fun, just for fun.

18:17.344 --> 18:34.389
If anything, this year has taught you that you can't put your confidence in your job, in the economy, in a political leader, even in the predictability of the weather, you need something more.

18:36.833 --> 18:40.178
And Mary is saying, God wants to give you exactly

18:40.674 --> 18:41.295
what you need.

18:43.237 --> 18:55.070
This is why Mary says that he shows his mercy, his kindness, his compassion, his heart, his tenderness, his love from generation to generation to all who fear him.

18:56.291 --> 19:10.066
And you need to catch this because God delights to show his mercy and his power and his love to those who know their need, their need.

19:10.754 --> 19:18.483
for God, their need for His help and who have the humility to open their lives to Him and what He has done.

19:19.364 --> 19:40.530
Because even as Mary talks about the tremendous arm of God and use it as an illustration for God's might and His strength, what she's also touching on is that the arms of God are forming in her womb, arms that will be stretched wide on a cross one day, to overcome sin and death and to bring freedom and life to every person everywhere.

19:42.914 --> 19:56.527
God is doing something incredible in her, and Mary is living proof that when the humble say yes to God, he does incredible things in them and through them and for them.

19:56.547 --> 20:01.072
But you face a very real threat to that reality in your lives that you may not be aware of.

20:01.692 --> 20:11.762
And Mary is focusing our attention on that threat when she says he satisfies the hungry with good things, but he sends the rich away hungry.

20:13.090 --> 20:15.694
You might be like, but what's the deal with that?

20:15.734 --> 20:16.796
The rich aren't going to be hungry.

20:16.816 --> 20:18.719
They're going to McDonald's and grabbing a burger if they need it.

20:18.739 --> 20:19.179
They're fine.

20:21.363 --> 20:25.789
Mary isn't just wanting to give us a dichotomy between those who have and those who have not.

20:27.091 --> 20:34.803
She's reminding you that all people are spiritually hungry, very hungry.

20:36.666 --> 20:42.034
And the rich tend to try to satisfy that hunger.

20:42.882 --> 20:51.322
With more and better, bigger house, nicer car, better image, more social status and followers, more experiences, vacations, what have you.

20:52.986 --> 20:55.431
But those can't satisfy.

20:56.374 --> 20:59.922
Those can't serve the deepest needs of the soul.

21:01.250 --> 21:03.333
You might be here saying, oh, okay, Luke, yeah, fair enough.

21:03.653 --> 21:10.801
I can think of some celebrities in the world's richest 1% who are just always buying the latest and greatest and jetting off to some vacation.

21:11.162 --> 21:12.724
But that's not me.

21:13.505 --> 21:16.048
That's not me.

21:16.068 --> 21:27.922
You know, if you're here and you have more than one outfit, pair of clothes, if you have food in your fridge, if you've got a shelter over your head, if you've got a job to go to,

21:28.962 --> 21:46.441
And if you've got some form of transportation, a bike, a motorbike, a car, maybe a skateboard, you're in the world's 10 to 20 richest percent that at least 80% of the world don't have every single one of those things.

21:50.105 --> 21:58.834
And Mary is saying, be careful because if you come to God saying, hey, look at what I've done.

21:59.234 --> 22:01.757
Look at my academic credentials.

22:02.758 --> 22:04.861
Look at my career success.

22:05.381 --> 22:06.783
Look at my online followers.

22:06.823 --> 22:08.485
Look at my bank account.

22:08.505 --> 22:09.166
Look what I've got.

22:09.286 --> 22:10.888
Also, if you could help me with this, that'd be great.

22:11.529 --> 22:12.971
You're gonna go away dissatisfied.

22:15.574 --> 22:29.010
But if you have the same posture as the world's poor who can't distract themselves from their need with more and better staff, who can't just buy what they want whenever they want it,

22:30.530 --> 22:31.471
It's called Amazon Prime.

22:33.975 --> 22:39.482
You come before God and you say, God, this is my need and only you can fill it.

22:41.084 --> 22:42.907
Only you can heal my broken heart.

22:43.047 --> 22:45.770
Only you can forgive me from the grateful things I've done.

22:46.311 --> 22:49.636
Only you can show me the wise way forward as the wise counselor.

22:50.216 --> 22:51.919
And only you can bring freedom and new life.

22:52.239 --> 23:00.370
And I open my hands to receive exactly what you are and what you are doing in me.

23:00.642 --> 23:02.465
Me, we are the rich.

23:05.169 --> 23:10.076
And yet joy is found through opening our lives in need to what God alone can do.

23:12.239 --> 23:20.872
It's amazing because so often when you think of world leaders and those who are wealthy or powerful, you think of all they gain and acquire and accomplish with their wealth.

23:22.334 --> 23:25.138
And yet Jesus invites us into a radically different way.

23:25.346 --> 23:28.529
Listen to this quote on how Jesus responds to power.

23:28.590 --> 23:31.393
It says power behaving humbly doesn't have much of a history.

23:32.053 --> 23:35.457
Humility wasn't even considered a virtue in the Roman world.

23:35.577 --> 23:37.780
Humility was a sign of weakness, not strength.

